        model: 'One <strong>benefit</strong> is that self-service kiosks speed up checkout, so <strong>customers</strong> spend less time queuing — a positive <strong>cultural</strong> impact. The <strong>company</strong> also gains, cutting wage costs and opening for longer. However, there are <strong>drawbacks</strong>: checkout staff (the <strong>employees</strong>) may lose their jobs, an <strong>ethical</strong>/social impact; and the discarded tills add to <strong>e-waste</strong> while always-on kiosks raise energy use — an <strong>environmental</strong> impact on the wider community. Because the facial-recognition images are personal data, the <strong>Data Protection Act 2018</strong> requires the supermarket to store them securely and use them only for age verification. <strong>Overall</strong>, the kiosks benefit customers and the business, but the company has a responsibility to retrain affected staff and safeguard the data it collects — so the decision is acceptable only with those safeguards in place.',
